If you are unhappy with hybrid return to school plans then make make masks and social distancing your #1 prirorty!” - Dr. Zywicki

New Jersey School Boards Association
July 2 at 2:40 PM ·

In a video interview, Dr. Robert Zywicki, superintendent of the Mount Olive School District in Morris County, discusses the reopening plans for his district with the NJSBA’s Ray Pinney. In the Mount Olive plan, there are four different options to deliver education to students. Dr. Zywicki discusses the positives and negatives of each, and he explains the thinking that went into the development of the district’s plan.
text:
New Jersey School Boards Association
July 2 at 2:40 PM ·

In a video interview, Dr. Robert Zywicki, superintendent of the Mount Olive School District in Morris County, discusses the reopening plans for his district with the NJSBA’s Ray Pinney. In the Mount Olive plan, there are four different options to deliver education to students. Dr. Zywicki discusses the positives and negatives of each, and he explains the thinking that went into the development of the district’s plan.

As per District Goal # 2, our Response to Intervention Manual, and our COVID Health-Related Closure Plan, we will be administering benchmarking assessments in the coming weeks to measure independent reading level, as well as, growth and proficiency in ELA and math. These multiple data points will inform recommendations for proactive summer intervention programs and placement recommendations for next year's courses in grades 6-12. Benchmarking assessments will be conducted in compliance with student IEPs and personalized learning plans. If you have any questions please contact Mr. Robinson or Mr. Stansberry.

post_text: MOMS 8th Grade Parents: This week, we secured a procedure for families to receive a 75% refund via post-payment trip insurance for the MOMS Washington, D.C. trip. We are also presently negotiating with the travel company to recoup the remaining 25% for a 100% total refund. This process has been slowed and complicated because the out-of-state travel company and their attorney are under a pandemic-related non-essential business operating restriction. That being said, we should have a final procedure for these refunds in place by the middle of next week. Thank you for your patience during this process. - Dr. Zywicki
text: MOMS 8th Grade Parents: This week, we secured a procedure for families to receive a 75% refund via post-payment trip insurance for the MOMS Washington, D.C. trip. We are also presently negotiating with the travel company to recoup the remaining 25% for a 100% total refund. This process has been slowed and complicated because the out-of-state travel company and their attorney are under a pandemic-related non-essential business operating restriction. That being said, we should have a final procedure for these refunds in place by the middle of next week. Thank you for your patience during this process. - Dr. Zywicki

post_text: Thank you to Dave Bodmer, Industrial Design and Engineering Teacher, for 3D printing face shield components in the MOHS Marauder Innovation Learning Lab (MILL). This is a collaborative effort with Rutgers and Montclair State to produce much needed personal protective gear for New Jersey’s frontline medical professionals fighting #COVID19. The MILL’s 35 3D printers will produce over 100 shield components a day.

post_text: Based on the executive order of Governor Murphy, the Mount Olive Township School District will be operating under a health-related closure for the indefinite future. Therefore, home instruction will be ongoing until April 8th. Spring break will remain as originally scheduled from April 9th until April 19th. If the health-related closure is still in effect, home instruction will resume on April 20th. Please go to tinyurl.com/MOhealthplan and view the MOTSD Health-Related Closure Plan that contains daily updates from Dr. Zywicki, as well as, vital information about home instruction assignments, WiFi access, free and reduced meal pick-up, and continuity of District operations.

post_text: This is a reminder that due to the health emergency, the Mount Olive Township School District will be closed from March 16, 2020 through March 27, 2020. We will reevaluate a reopening date on March 27th. All athletics and activities are suspended until at least March 30th. Please go to tinyurl.com/MOhealthplan and view the Health-Related Closure Plan that contains vital information about home instruction assignments, WiFi access, free and reduced meal pick-up, and continuity of District operations.

post_text: Effective March 12, 2020 and continuing until March 31, 2020, all field trips, as well as, evening and weekend activities are postponed. All facility use events and rental activities are canceled including those in the Marauder Dome. Athletics will continue at the direction of the NJSIAA. MOHS student clubs and activities that are contiguous with the school day will continue. MO Success Academy, ASPIRE, and AlphaBest will continue at regularly scheduled times. This decision is based on advice from MO Department of Health, guidance from the CDC, cancellations by some of our participants/event partners, and an abundance of caution when it comes to out of state travel.

post_text: This evening Mount Olive Police Department informed the District's administration of a threat made via Instagram towards Mount Olive High School. The threat has been investigated and deemed to be non-credible by MOPD. There will be an increased police presence at Mount Olive High School throughout the day tomorrow 5/2/19. Updates will be provided if further information about the investigation becomes available.
